    {"practice":"1","code":"SM-9","subCode":"undefined","explanation":"The requirement mandates a structured process to assess and mitigate security risks associated with externally sourced components integrated into industrial control systems (ICS).","context":"Externally provided components, such as third-party software or hardware, can introduce vulnerabilities if not properly vetted, impacting the overall security posture of ICS environments.","challenges":["Lack of visibility into third-party component security: Many vendors do not disclose full security details, making risk assessment difficult. Example: A PLC module with undocumented backdoor access.","Inconsistent security standards across suppliers: Different vendors follow varying security practices. Example: A sensor manufacturer may not adhere to secure coding standards.","Difficulty in patch management: Third-party components may have delayed or unavailable patches. Example: A legacy HMI software with no updates for known vulnerabilities.","Integration complexities: Ensuring secure interoperability between external and internal components. Example: A third-party communication protocol introducing buffer overflow risks.","Supply chain risks: Compromised components introduced during manufacturing or distribution. Example: A counterfeit network card with embedded malware."],"best_practices":[{"description":"Establish a vendor security assessment program to evaluate third-party components before integration. Example: Requiring suppliers to complete a security questionnaire aligned with IEC 62443-4-1.","url":" https://www.siemens.com/global/en/products/services/cert/security-advisories.html","url_description":"Siemens' security advisories provide insights into vulnerabilities in third-party ICS components."},{"description":"Implement a software bill of materials (SBOM) to track all external components. Example: Using tools like OWASP Dependency-Track to monitor open-source libraries.","url":" https://www.isa.org/standards-and-publications/isa-standards/isa-iec-62443-series-of-standards","url_description":"ISA's guidelines on SBOM implementation for ICS security."},{"description":"Require vendors to provide security certifications or attestations for their components. Example: Only procuring devices with ISA/IEC 62443-4-2 certification.","url":" https://www.honeywellprocess.com/library/support/notifications/cybersecurity/Pages/default.aspx","url_description":"Honeywell's cybersecurity notifications for third-party component vulnerabilities."},{"description":"Conduct regular security audits of third-party components in operational environments. Example: Periodic penetration testing of vendor-supplied HMI software.","url":" https://www.schneider-electric.com/en/work/support/cybersecurity/security-notifications.jsp","url_description":"Schneider Electric's security notifications for external components."}],"key_aspects":[{"id":"KA1","title":"Vendor Security Assessment","description":"A formal process to evaluate third-party vendors' security practices, ensuring alignment with IEC 62443-4-1 requirements before component integration.","related_links":[{"title":"Rockwell Automation Supplier Security Requirements","url":"https://www.rockwellautomation.com/en-us/company/information/security.html","description":"Rockwell's framework for assessing supplier security capabilities."},{"title":"ABB Third-Party Risk Management","url":"https://new.abb.com/about/technology/cyber-security","description":"ABB's approach to managing risks from external components."}]},{"id":"KA2","title":"Component Vulnerability Monitoring","description":"Continuous monitoring of external components for newly discovered vulnerabilities through vendor notifications and security bulletins.","related_links":[{"title":"CISA ICS Advisories","url":"https://www.cisa.gov/ics/advisories","description":"Official vulnerability disclosures for ICS components."},{"title":"Siemens ProductCERT","url":"https://cert-portal.