    {"practice":"1","code":"SM-11","subCode":"e) defect management (see Clause 10, Practice 6 – Management of security-related issues).","explanation":"The requirement mandates a structured process to ensure that products or patches are not released until all identified security-related issues are resolved and documented. This includes tracking defects from identification to closure.","context":"In industrial control systems (ICS), unresolved security defects can lead to vulnerabilities exploitable by attackers, potentially causing operational disruptions or safety incidents. Effective defect management is critical for maintaining system integrity.","challenges":["Identifying all security-related defects during development or patch cycles. Example: A zero-day vulnerability in a PLC firmware update may go undetected without thorough testing.","Prioritizing defects based on risk. Example: A critical buffer overflow in an HMI must be addressed before minor UI bugs.","Ensuring timely resolution of defects. Example: A patch for a SCADA system vulnerability may be delayed due to vendor backlog.","Tracking defects across distributed teams. Example: A defect reported by a field engineer may not reach the development team promptly.","Maintaining documentation for compliance audits. Example: An auditor may require proof that all defects in a release were resolved."],"best_practices":[{"description":"Implement automated static and dynamic code analysis tools to detect security defects early. Example: Using Coverity for static analysis in ICS software development.","url":" https://www.synopsys.com/software-integrity/resources/analyst-reports/coverity-static-analysis.html","url_description":"Synopsys Coverity for static analysis in ICS software development."},{"description":"Establish a risk-based defect triage process. Example: Using CVSS scores to prioritize vulnerabilities in ICS patches.","url":"https://www.first.org/cvss/","url_description":"FIRST CVSS for risk-based vulner