    {"practice":"2","code":"SR-2","subCode":"a) correct flow of categorized information throughout the system;","explanation":"Threat modeling ensures that information flows securely within industrial control systems (ICS), identifying potential vulnerabilities and misconfigurations that could compromise data integrity or confidentiality.","context":"In ICS environments, threat modeling is critical to prevent unauthorized access or manipulation of categorized information, which could disrupt operations or lead to safety incidents.","challenges":["Identifying all data flows in complex ICS architectures, especially in legacy systems with undocumented communication paths.","Example: A legacy SCADA system may have unsecured data flows between HMIs and PLCs that are not documented.","Ensuring consistent categorization of information (e.g., critical vs. non-critical) across different subsystems.","Example: A power plant may misclassify sensor data as non-critical, leading to inadequate protection measures.","Integrating threat modeling with existing development lifecycles without causing delays.","Example: A vendor rushing a product release may skip threat modeling for new features.","Addressing zero-day vulnerabilities that are not yet documented in threat databases.","Example: A new ICS protocol vulnerability could bypass existing threat models.","Balancing security controls with real-time performance requirements in ICS.","Example: Encryption may introduce latency in a gas pipeline's control system."],"best_practices":[{"description":"Use automated tools like Microsoft Threat Modeling Tool or IriusRisk to map data flows and identify threats systematically.","url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/security/develop/threat-modeling-tool","url_description":"Microsoft's guide on using their Threat Modeling Tool for ICS data flow analysis."},{"description":"Adopt the STRIDE framework (Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Information Disclosure, DoS, Elevation of Privilege) to categorize threats.","url":" https://www.siemens.com/global/en/products/services/cert/security-advisories.html","url_description":"Siemens' advisories demonstrate STRIDE applications in ICS threat models."},{"description":"Conduct regular threat model reviews with cross-functional teams (security, OT, engineering).","url":" https://www.honeywellprocess.com/library/support/publications/cybersecurity/Pages/default.aspx","url_description":"Honeywell's whitepapers on collaborative threat modeling for process control systems."},{"description":"Document assumptions and constraints (e.g., legacy protocol limitations) explicitly in the threat model.","url":" https://www.isa.org/standards-and-publications/isa-standards/isa-iec-62443-series-of-standards","url_description":"ISA/IEC 62443 standards provide templates for ICS threat model documentation."},{"description":"Validate threat models against real-world attack scenarios (e.g., Stuxnet-style attacks).","url":"https://www.cisa.gov/resources-tools/services/shields-ready","url_description":"CISA's SHIELDS program offers ICS-specific attack simulations for validation."}],"key_aspects":[{"id":"KA1","title":"Data Flow Mapping","description":"Comprehensive documentation of all information pathways between ICS components, including protocols and interfaces. Critical for identifying unauthorized data exfiltration points.","related_links":[{"title":"Rockwell Automation Data Flow Diagrams","url":"https://www.rockwellautomation.com/en-us/products/security.html","description":"Rockwell's guidelines for mapping ICS data flows in FactoryTalk environments."},{"title":"NIST SP 800-82 Rev.3 ICS Security","url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/SpecialPublications/NIST.SP.800-82r3.pdf","description":"NIST's framework for ICS data flow analysis (Section 3.1.2)."}]},{"id":"KA2","title":"Information Categorization","description":"Classification of data by criticality (e.g., safety-related vs. operational) to apply appropriate security c