    {"practice":"2","code":"SR-2","subCode":"b) trust boundaries;","explanation":"Threat modeling for trust boundaries identifies where data or control transitions between different security levels or domains within an ICS, ensuring proper security controls are in place.","context":"Trust boundaries are critical in ICS environments where operational technology (OT) and information technology (IT) systems interact, requiring clear demarcation to prevent unauthorized access or data leakage.","challenges":["Identifying all trust boundaries in complex ICS architectures, especially in legacy systems with undocumented interfaces.","Ensuring consistent security controls across trust boundaries, such as firewalls or encryption, without disrupting operational continuity.","Managing dynamic trust boundaries in virtualized or cloud-based ICS environments where boundaries may shift frequently.","Addressing human factors, such as misconfigurations by operators when crossing trust boundaries during maintenance or updates.","Validating trust boundary assumptions through penetration testing, which can be resource-intensive in OT environments."],"best_practices":[{"description":"Document trust boundaries in network diagrams, highlighting interfaces between IT/OT zones. Example: A power plant marks boundaries between SCADA and corporate networks with VLANs and firewalls.","url":"https://www.siemens.com/industrial-security","url_description":"Siemens’ guide on ICS network segmentation aligns with SR-2(b) for visualizing trust boundaries."},{"description":"Implement micro-segmentation within OT networks to enforce granular trust boundaries. Example: A refinery uses software-defined perimeters to isolate critical PLCs.","url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/solutions/industries/industrial-iot/security.html","url_description":"Cisco’s IIoT security whitepaper details micro-segmentation for ICS trust boundaries."},{"description":"Use hardware-enforced boundaries (e.g., unidirectional gatew