    {"practice":"2","code":"SR-5","subCode":"a) architects/developers (those who will implement the requirements);","explanation":"The requirement mandates a structured process to review and validate security requirements, ensuring they are clear, aligned with the threat model, and verifiable. Architects and developers must actively participate in this process.","context":"This practice is critical in ICS environments where security requirements must address unique operational and safety constraints. It ensures that security measures are feasible and effective against identified threats.","challenges":["Lack of clear communication between security teams and developers can lead to misinterpretation of requirements. Example: A developer might overlook a critical security constraint in a PLC configuration.","Evolving threat landscapes may render initial requirements obsolete. Example: A new ICS-specific malware emerges, requiring updates to the threat model and security requirements.","Balancing security with operational efficiency is challenging. Example: Implementing stringent authentication might delay critical processes in a manufacturing plant.","Ensuring all stakeholders (e.g., engineers, IT, management) are aligned. Example: A security requirement might conflict with legacy system capabilities, causing disputes.","Verification of requirements can be resource-intensive. Example: Testing a new firewall rule in a live ICS environment without disrupting operations."],"best_practices":[{"description":"Conduct regular cross-functional workshops to align security requirements with operational needs. Example: Siemens' guide on collaborative security design for ICS provides practical steps for such workshops.","url":" https://new.siemens.com/global/en/products/automation/industry-security/industrial-security/security-lifecycle.html","url_description":"Siemens' guide on integrating security into the ICS lifecycle, relevant for SR-5."},{"description":"Use threat modeling tools like Microsoft Threat Modeling Tool to visualize and validate requirements. Example: A water treatment plant used this tool to identify gaps in access control requirements.","url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/security/develop/threat-modeling-tool","url_description":"Microsoft's tool for threat modeling, applicable to ICS security requirements."},{"description":"Document requirements in a traceable format (e.g., using JIRA or DOORS). Example: A power grid operator traced security requirements from design to testing, ensuring consistency.","url":"https://www.ibm.com/products/doors","url_description":"IBM DOORS for requirement management, useful for SR-5 compliance."},{"description":"Leverage vendor-specific security guidelines (e.g., Rockwell Automation's Secure Development Lifecycle) to inform requirements. Example: A factory adopted Rockwell's guidelines to harden HMI configurations.","url":" https://www.rockwellautomation.com/en-us/company/about-us/sustainability/cybersecurity.html","url_description":"Rockwell's cybersecurity resources, including secure development practices."}],"key_aspects":[{"id":"KA1","title":"Threat Model Alignment","description":"Ensures security requirements are derived from and consistent with the threat model. Critical for addressing ICS-specific threats like unauthorized access to SCADA systems.","related_links":[{"title":"ISA/IEC 62443-3-2 Threat Modeling Guide","url":" https://www.isa.org/standards-and-publications/isa-standards/isa-iec-62443-series-of-standards/isa-iec-62443-3-2","description":"ISA's guide on threat modeling for ICS, aligned with SR-5."},{"title":"NIST SP 800-82 ICS Security Guide","url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-82/rev-2/final","description":"NIST's ICS security guidelines, including threat modeling."}]},{"id":"KA2","title":"Requirement Traceability","description":"Maintains a clear link between requirements, design, and testing. Essential for verifying that security controls a