    {"practice":"2","code":"SR-5","subCode":"b) testers (those who will validate that the requirements have been met);","explanation":"The requirement mandates an independent review process for security requirements by testers to ensure clarity, validity, and alignment with the threat model. Testers must remain independent to avoid conflicts of interest.","context":"In industrial control systems (ICS), security requirements must be verifiable and aligned with operational threats. Independent testers ensure unbiased validation of these requirements.","challenges":["Ensuring tester independence: Testers must not be involved in requirement development to avoid bias. Example: A vendor uses the same team for development and testing, leading to overlooked vulnerabilities.","Lack of ICS-specific expertise: Testers may lack knowledge of industrial protocols. Example: A tester unfamiliar with Modbus misses a critical security flaw in communication.","Dynamic threat landscape: Requirements may become outdated quickly. Example: A new ICS ransomware variant emerges, rendering existing test cases ineffective.","Resource constraints: Limited testing personnel can delay validation. Example: A small team struggles to test all security requirements before deployment.","Documentation gaps: Incomplete requirement documentation hampers testing. Example: Testers cannot verify a requirement due to ambiguous wording."],"best_practices":[{"description":"Establish a dedicated testing team separate from development to ensure independence. Example: A power plant assigns a third-party team to validate security requirements.","url":"https://www.sans.org/white-papers/36067/","url_description":"SANS paper on ICS testing independence."},{"description":"Train testers on ICS-specific protocols and threats. Example: A tester undergoes training on PROFINET security before validating requirements.","url":" https://www.isa.org/standards-and-publications/isa-standards/isa-62443-standards","url_description":"ISA standards for ICS security training."},{"description":"Use automated tools to supplement manual testing. Example: A tester employs a SCADA vulnerability scanner to validate requirements.","url":" https://www.trellix.com/en-us/assets/white-papers/wp-industrial-control-systems.pdf","url_description":"Trellix guide on ICS testing tools."},{"description":"Regularly update test cases to reflect new threats. Example: A tester incorporates Stuxnet-like scenarios into test cases.","url":"https://www.cisa.gov/resources-tools/services/shields-ready","url_description":"CISA's threat-informed testing resources."}],"key_aspects":[{"id":"KA1","title":"Tester Independence","description":"Ensuring testers are independent from requirement development prevents conflicts of interest and biases, critical for objective validation in ICS environments.","related_links":[{"title":"NIST SP 800-82 ICS Security Guide","url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/SpecialPublications/NIST.SP.800-82r3.pdf","description":"NIST guidelines on ICS security testing independence."},{"title":"Siemens ICS Security Testing","url":" https://www.siemens.com/global/en/products/services/cert/security-services/industrial-security-services.html","description":"Siemens' approach to independent ICS security testing."}]},{"id":"KA2","title":"ICS-Specific Testing Expertise","description":"Testers must understand industrial protocols and threats to effectively validate security requirements in ICS environments.","related_links":[{"title":"Rockwell Automation ICS Security","url":"https://www.rockwellautomation.com/en-us/capabilities/cybersecurity.html","description":"Rockwell's resources on ICS security testing."},{"title":"ICS-CERT Advisories","url":"https://www.cisa.gov/resources-tools/services/ics-cert-advisories","description":"Latest ICS threats for tester awareness."}]},{"id":"KA3","title":"Dynamic Test Case Management","description":"Regular updates to test cases ensure they remain relevant to evolving IC