    {"practice":"3","code":"SD-1","subCode":"d) a determination of whether access to the interface crosses a trust boundary;","explanation":"This requirement ensures that all interfaces (physical and logical) are analyzed to determine if they cross trust boundaries, which is critical for identifying potential security risks in ICS environments.","context":"In industrial control systems, interfaces often connect different security zones. Identifying trust boundaries helps in applying appropriate security controls to prevent unauthorized access or data leakage.","challenges":["Identifying all interfaces in complex ICS architectures, especially legacy systems with undocumented connections.","Example: A PLC in a manufacturing plant has undocumented serial ports used for maintenance, crossing a trust boundary.","Determining trust boundaries in hybrid environments where IT and OT networks intersect.","Example: A SCADA system connected to a corporate network via a firewall, but with insufficient segmentation.","Lack of standardized documentation for interfaces in multi-vendor environments.","Example: Different vendors use proprietary protocols, making boundary analysis difficult.","Dynamic environments where interfaces change frequently due to reconfigurations or updates.","Example: A temporary VPN connection for remote support that remains active unintentionally.","Balancing security with operational requirements, such as real-time data access across boundaries.","Example: A historian server needs data from control systems but must not expose sensitive control commands."],"best_practices":[{"description":"Conduct a thorough inventory of all interfaces, including physical ports and network connections, using automated tools where possible.","url":"https://www.siemens.com/industrial-security","url_description":"Siemens guide on ICS interface inventory and trust boundary analysis."},{"description":"Use network segmentation to enforce trust boundaries, such as VLANs or firewalls, and document the segmentation rationale.","url":" https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/solutions/industries/manufacturing/industrial-security.html","url_description":"Cisco's approach to network segmentation in industrial environments."},{"description":"Implement role-based access control (RBAC) for interfaces crossing trust boundaries to limit exposure.","url":" https://www.honeywellprocess.com/library/support/technical-notes/secure-remote-access.pdf","url_description":"Honeywell's technical note on secure remote access and RBAC."},{"description":"Regularly audit interface configurations and access logs to detect unauthorized boundary crossings.","url":" https://www.schneider-electric.com/en/work/solutions/system/files/solution-files/cybersecurity-guide.pdf","url_description":"Schneider Electric's guide on ICS interface auditing and monitoring."}],"key_aspects":[{"id":"KA1","title":"Interface Inventory Documentation","description":"Maintaining a comprehensive inventory of all interfaces is essential for identifying trust boundaries. This includes physical ports, network connections, and wireless interfaces, documented with their security zones.","related_links":[{"title":"Rockwell Automation Interface Security Guide","url":"https://www.rockwellautomation.com/en-us/solutions/cybersecurity.html","description":"Rockwell's guide on documenting and securing ICS interfaces."},{"title":"ISA Technical Report on ICS Interface Management","url":"https://www.isa.org/standards-and-publications/isa-standards","description":"ISA's technical report on best practices for interface management in ICS."}]},{"id":"KA2","title":"Trust Boundary Mapping","description":"Mapping interfaces to trust boundaries involves analyzing data flows and access controls. This helps in applying appropriate security measures, such as encryption or authentication, at boundary crossings.","related_links":[{"title":"Yokogawa Trust Boundary Analysis Whitepaper","url":"https://www.yokogawa.com/solutions/products-platforms/control-system/security/","description":"Yokogawa's whitepaper on trust boundary analysis in ICS."},{"title":"ABB Industrial Security Reference Architecture","url":"https://new.abb.com/control-systems/security","description":"ABB's reference architecture for mapping trust boundaries in ICS."}]},{"id":"KA3","title":"Access Control Enforcement","description":"Enforcing strict access controls at trust boundaries prevents unauthorized access. This includes authentication, authorization, and accounting (AAA) mechanisms for all boundary-crossing interfaces.","related_links":[{"title":"Siemens Industrial Security Best Practices","url":"https://www.siemens.com/industrial-security","description":"Siemens' best practices for access control at ICS trust boundaries."},{"title":"NIST SP 800-82 Rev. 3 ICS Security Guide","url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-82/rev-3/final","description":"NIST's guidelines on access control for ICS trust boundaries."}]},{"id":"KA4","title":"Dynamic Interface Monitoring","description":"Continuous monitoring of interfaces is critical to detect changes or unauthorized boundary crossings. This includes real-time logging and alerting for suspicious activities.","related_links":[{"title":"Schneider Electric ICS Monitoring Guide","url":"https://www.se.com/ww/en/work/solutions/cybersecurity/","description":"Schneider's guide on monitoring ICS interfaces for security."},{"title":"Honeywell Industrial Cybersecurity Solutions","url":" https://www.honeywellprocess.com/en-US/explore/products/industrial-cybersecurity/Pages/default.aspx","description":"Honeywell's solutions for dynamic interface monitoring in ICS."}]}],"name":"Secure design principles","description":"A process shall be employed for developing and documenting a secure design that identifies and characterizes each interface of the product, including physical and logical interfaces, to include: d) a determination of whether access to the interface crosses a trust boundary;","details":{"risk_assessment_and_threat_modeling":{"why":"Identifying trust boundaries is critical to understanding potential attack vectors and ensuring secure communication between components.","methodologies":[{"name":"STRIDE","description":"Used to categorize threats into Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Information Disclosure, Denial of Service, and Elevation of Privilege."},{"name":"ICS-specific threat models","description":"Focuses on industrial control systems, considering operational technology (OT) constraints and legacy protocols."}],"tools":[{"name":"Microsoft Threat Modeling Tool","purpose":"Assists in identifying and mitigating potential security issues early in the development lifecycle."},{"name":"NIST 800-30 adapted for SCADA systems","purpose":"Provides a structured approach for assessing risks in industrial control systems."}],"case_study":{"example":"A power plant's DCS was assessed using STRIDE to identify trust boundaries between the control network and corporate IT network, leading to the implementation of additional firewall rules and network segmentation."}},"audit_and_compliance_verification":{"why":"Ensures that the secure design principles are consistently applied and documented.","audit_checklist":["Verify that all interfaces are documented, including physical and logical interfaces.","Check if trust boundary crossings are identified and mitigated.","Review documentation for evidence of threat modeling and risk assessment."],"metrics":[{"kpi":"Percentage of interfaces with documented trust boundary analysis","target":"100%"},{"kpi":"Number of unresolved high-risk trust boundary issues","target":"0"}],"compliance_procedure":"Documentation must include interface characterization, threat modeling results, and mitigation strategies. Regular reviews by the security team are required."},"training_and_competency_requirements":{"why":"Ensures that personnel involved in secure design have the necessary skills and knowledge.","training_pro