    {"practice":"3","code":"SD-4","subCode":"b) using proven secure components/designs where possible;","explanation":"The requirement mandates the use of secure, well-tested components and designs in industrial control systems to minimize vulnerabilities. This reduces the attack surface and enhances system resilience.","context":"In ICS environments, legacy systems and proprietary components often lack modern security features. Using proven secure components mitigates risks associated with outdated or insecure technologies.","challenges":["Legacy system integration: Older ICS components may not support modern security features, complicating secure integration. Example: Integrating a legacy PLC with a new secure gateway.","Vendor lock-in: Proprietary components may limit the ability to implement third-party secure solutions. Example: A vendor-specific HMI with no support for standard encryption.","Performance trade-offs: Secure components may introduce latency or resource overhead. Example: Encryption on low-power RTUs affecting real-time performance.","Supply chain risks: Dependence on untrusted vendors for secure components. Example: A compromised firmware update from a third-party supplier.","Lack of documentation: Incomplete or unclear documentation on secure configurations. Example: A vendor-provided manual missing secure deployment guidelines."],"best_practices":[{"description":"Use vendor-validated secure components with documented security features. Example: Deploying a Siemens S7-1500 PLC with built-in secure boot and encrypted communications.","url":" https://new.siemens.com/global/en/products/automation/systems/industrial/plc/s7-1500.html","url_description":"Siemens S7-1500 security features documentation, aligned with SD-4."},{"description":"Implement secure-by-design architectures, such as zero-trust networks. Example: Segmenting ICS networks using firewalls with deep packet inspection.","url":" https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/solutions/enterprise-networks/zero-trust-security.html","url_description":"Cisco’s guide on zero-trust for ICS, relevant to SD-4."},{"description":"Regularly audit and update component security configurations. Example: Using Rockwell Automation’s FactoryTalk AssetCentre for configuration management.","url":" https://www.rockwellautomation.com/en-us/products/software/enterprise/factorytalk-assetcentre.html","url_description":"Rockwell’s tool for secure configuration management, applicable to SD-4."},{"description":"Leverage industry standards like ISA/IEC 62443 for component selection. Example: Choosing an IACS component certified under ISA/IEC 62443-4-2.","url":" https://www.isa.org/standards-and-publications/isa-standards/isa-iec-62443-series-of-standards","url_description":"ISA/IEC 62443 standards for secure component selection."}],"key_aspects":[{"id":"KA1","title":"Secure Component Certification","description":"Ensuring components are certified under recognized standards (e.g., ISA/IEC 62443-4-2) guarantees baseline security features. Critical for SD-4 compliance.","related_links":[{"title":"ISA/IEC 62443-4-2 Certification Guide","url":" https://www.isa.org/standards-and-publications/isa-standards/isa-iec-62443-series-of-standards","description":"Guidance on component certification under ISA/IEC 62443-4-2."},{"title":"Schneider Electric Secure Component List","url":" https://www.se.com/ww/en/work/solutions/system/s1/cybersecurity/secure-components.jsp","description":"Schneider’s list of pre-validated secure components for ICS."}]},{"id":"KA2","title":"Vendor Security Assessments","description":"Evaluating vendor security practices ensures reliable supply chains. Includes reviewing vulnerability disclosure policies and patch management.","related_links":[{"title":"NIST Supplier Risk Management Guide","url":" https://www.nist.gov/publications/cybersecurity-supply-chain-risk-management-practics-systems-and-organizations","description":"NIST guidelines for assessing vendor security."},{"title":"Honeywell ICS Vendor Checklist","url":" https://www.honeywellprocess.com/library/support/Public/Documents/Cybersecurity-Vendor-Assessment.pdf","description":"Honeywell’s checklist for ICS vendor security."}]},{"id":"KA3","title":"Secure Design Patterns","description":"Adopting patterns like defense-in-depth minimizes single points of failure. Example: Layered network segmentation in ICS architectures.","related_links":[{"title":"Cisco Defense-in-Depth for ICS","url":" https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/solutions/industries/manufacturing/industrial-security.html","description":"Cisco’s approach to layered ICS security."},{"title":"Siemens Industrial Security Whitepaper","url":" https://assets.new.siemens.com/siemens/assets/api/uuid:9b5b5b5b-5b5b-5b5b-5b5b-5b5b5b5b5b5b/whitepaper-industrial-security.pdf","description":"Siemens’ whitepaper on secure ICS design patterns."}]},{"id":"KA4","title":"Component Hardening Guidelines","description":"Documenting and applying hardening measures (e.g., disabling unused services) reduces attack surfaces. Essential for SD-4 subCode b.","related_links":[{"title":"Rockwell Automation Hardening Guide","url":" https://literature.rockwellautomation.com/idc/groups/literature/documents/at/enet-at002_-en-p.pdf","description":"Rockwell’s ICS component hardening manual."},{"title":"MITRE ICS Hardening Recommendations","url":" https://www.mitre.org/publications/technical-papers/hardening-industrial-control-systems","description":"MITRE’s technical paper on ICS hardening."}]}],"name":"Secure design best practices","description":"A process shall be employed to ensure that secure design best practices are documented and applied to the design process. These practices shall be periodically reviewed and updated. Secure design practices include but are not be limited to: b) using proven secure components/designs where possible;","details":{"risk_assessment_and_threat_modeling":{"why":"To identify potential vulnerabilities in components and designs before implementation.","methodologies":[{"name":"STRIDE","description":"A threat modeling methodology that identifies Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Information Disclosure, Denial of Service, and Elevation of Privilege threats."},{"name":"ICS-specific threat models","description":"Custom threat models tailored for Industrial Control Systems, focusing on operational technology (OT) risks."}],"tools":[{"name":"Microsoft Threat Modeling Tool","purpose":"To create and analyze threat models using the STRIDE methodology."},{"name":"NIST 800-30 adapted for SCADA systems","purpose":"A risk assessment framework tailored for SCADA and ICS environments."}],"case_study":{"example":"A power plant used STRIDE to assess threats in their Distributed Control System (DCS), identifying critical tampering risks in legacy PLCs."}},"audit_and_compliance_verification":{"why":"To ensure adherence to secure design practices and identify gaps.","audit_checklist":["Verify documentation of secure design practices.","Check for evidence of periodic reviews and updates to design practices.","Review component selection criteria for security considerations."],"metrics":[{"kpi":"Percentage of components with documented security assessments","target":"100%"},{"kpi":"Number of design practice updates per year","target":"At least 2"}],"compliance_procedure":"Documentation must include component security assessments, design practice reviews, and update logs. Evidence is reviewed quarterly by the security team."},"training_and_competency_requirements":{"why":"To ensure personnel are capable of applying secure design practices.","training_programs":[{"name":"ISA/IEC 62443 Cybersecurity Fundamentals Specialist","description":"Covers secure design principles for ICS components."},{"name":"GICSP (Global Industrial Cyber Security Professional)","description":"Provides training on securing industrial systems, including design best practices."}],"competency_assessment":"Annual reviews of design engineers' competency in secure design practices, including practical assessments of component selection."},"tooling_and_automation_support":{"why":"To streamline the application of secure design practices.","tools":[{"name":"Static Application Security Testing (SAST) tools","purpose":"To analyze code for vulnerabilities during the design phase."},{"name":"Software Bill of Materials (SBOM) tools","purpose":"To track and verify the security of third-party components."}],"automation_strategy":"Integrate SAST and SBOM tools into the CI/CD pipeline to automatically flag insecure components during design."},"handling_legacy_systems_and_constraints":{"why":"Legacy systems often cannot meet modern security standards, requiring compensatory measures.","strategies":[{"approach":"Network segmentation","description":"Isolate legacy components in separate network zones to limit exposure."},{"approach":"Secure gateway deployment","description":"Use secure gateways to mediate communications between legacy and modern systems."}],"example_policy":"Legacy components must be documented, risk-assessed, and isolated if they cannot meet current security standards. Compensating controls must be implemented and reviewed annually."},"stakeholder_collaboration_and_governance":{"why":"Secure design requires coordination between engineering, security, and management teams.","governance_model":{"name":"RACI Matrix for Secure Design","roles":[{"role":"Engineering Team","responsibility":"Implement secure design practices and document component selections."},{"role":"Security Team","responsibility":"Review and approve design practices and component choices."},{"role":"Management","responsibility":"Allocate resources and enforce compliance with design policies."}]},"conflict_resolution":"Disputes between engineering and security teams are escalated to a cross-functional review board, which makes binding decisions based on risk assessments."},"continuous_improvement_and_updates":{"why":"To adapt to evolving threats