    {"practice":"6","code":"DM-4","subCode":"3) use of compensating mechanisms; and/or","explanation":"Compensating mechanisms are temporary or alternative controls implemented to mitigate security risks when primary controls are not feasible. They ensure residual risk remains within acceptable levels.","context":"In ICS environments, compensating mechanisms are often necessary due to legacy systems, operational constraints, or unpatched vulnerabilities. They provide interim protection while long-term solutions are developed.","challenges":["Identifying suitable compensating controls for legacy ICS devices with limited security features. Example: Using network segmentation to isolate an unpatched PLC.","Ensuring compensating mechanisms do not disrupt operational continuity. Example: Deploying an intrusion detection system (IDS) without causing latency in real-time communications.","Validating the effectiveness of compensating controls in reducing risk. Example: Testing a firewall rule set to verify it blocks unauthorized access to a vulnerable HMI.","Maintaining compensating mechanisms over time as threats evolve. Example: Regularly updating whitelisting rules for an application control solution.","Documenting and communicating compensating controls to all stakeholders. Example: Creating a risk register that outlines temporary measures for a vulnerable SCADA system."],"best_practices":[{"description":"Implement network segmentation to isolate vulnerable devices. Example: Using VLANs to separate legacy equipment from critical systems.","url":" https://www.cisa.gov/sites/default/files/publications/20_0309_cisa_ncsd_ics-security-essentials-network-segmentation.pdf","url_description":"CISA guide on network segmentation for ICS, relevant to DM-4 subCode 3."},{"description":"Deploy host-based intrusion detection systems (HIDS) on critical servers. Example: Using OSSEC to monitor file integrity on a historian server.","url":"https://www.sans.org/white-papers/35773/","url_description":"SANS paper on HIDS deployment in ICS, aligned with DM-4 subCode 3."},{"description":"Apply application whitelisting to prevent unauthorized software execution. Example: Using Microsoft AppLocker on engineering workstations.","url":"https://www.nist.gov/publications/guide-application-whitelisting","url_description":"NIST guide on application whitelisting, pertinent to compensating controls."},{"description":"Use out-of-band monitoring for systems that cannot support agents. Example: Deploying passive network taps to monitor OT traffic.","url":"https://www.dragos.com/wp-content/uploads/PassiveNetworkMonitoringinICS.pdf","url_description":"Dragos whitepaper on passive monitoring in ICS, relevant to DM-4 subCode 3."}],"key_aspects":[{"id":"KA1","title":"Risk-Based Control Selection","description":"Compensating mechanisms must be selected based on a thorough risk assessment to ensure they adequately address the identified vulnerabilities without introducing new risks.","related_links":[{"title":"ISA/IEC 62443-3-2 Risk Assessment Methodology","url":" https://www.isa.org/products/ansi-isa-62443-3-2-security-for-industrial-automation","description":"ISA's methodology for risk assessment in ICS, critical for DM-4 subCode 3."},{"title":"NIST SP 800-82 Guide to ICS Security","url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-82/rev-2/final","description":"NIST guidelines for implementing compensating controls in ICS."}]},{"id":"KA2","title":"Temporary Control Documentation","description":"All compensating mechanisms must be clearly documented, including their purpose, implementation details, and planned duration, to ensure proper oversight and eventual replacement.","related_links":[{"title":"CISA Compensating Controls Guide","url":"https://www.cisa.gov/resources-tools/services/cyber-resilience-review","description":"CISA's framework for documenting compensating controls."},{"title":"Siemens ICS Security Whitepaper","url":" https://new.siemens.com/global/en/p