    {"practice":"6","code":"DM-4","subCode":"4) disabling or removing features;","explanation":"The process involves identifying and mitigating security risks by disabling or removing non-essential features that could introduce vulnerabilities in industrial control systems (ICS).","context":"In ICS environments, unnecessary features can increase attack surfaces. Disabling or removing them reduces potential entry points for attackers while maintaining operational integrity.","challenges":["Identifying non-critical features without impacting core functionality. Example: A legacy SCADA system may rely on deprecated protocols that cannot be easily removed.","Assessing the security impact of each feature. Example: A web interface in a PLC may be convenient but poses significant risks if not properly secured.","Managing stakeholder resistance to feature removal. Example: Operators may oppose disabling remote access due to convenience, despite security risks.","Ensuring compatibility with existing systems post-removal. Example: Disabling a legacy protocol may break communication with older devices.","Documenting changes for audit and compliance. Example: Failing to record disabled features may lead to non-compliance with IEC 62443-4-1."],"best_practices":[{"description":"Conduct a thorough risk assessment before disabling features. Example: Evaluate whether a web server in an RTU is necessary for operations or can be disabled. Link: Siemens guide on secure RTU configurations.","url":" https://new.siemens.com/global/en/products/automation/industry-software/automation-software/tia-portal.html","url_description":"Siemens' guide on secure configurations for RTUs, relevant to DM-4 subCode 4."},{"description":"Implement change management procedures for feature removal. Example: Use a ticketing system to track and approve feature disablement in ICS devices. Link: Rockwell Automation's change management whitepaper.","url":"https://www.rockwellautomation.com/en-us/capabilities/cybersecurity.html","url_description":"Rockwell's whitepaper on ICS change management, aligned with DM-4 requirements."},{"description":"Test feature removal in a non-production environment first. Example: Disable SNMP in a test PLC to verify no operational impact before deploying to production. Link: Schneider Electric's ICS testing guide.","url":"https://www.se.com/ww/en/work/solutions/system/s1/cybersecurity/","url_description":"Schneider's guide on testing ICS configurations, applicable to DM-4 subCode 4."},{"description":"Document all disabled features and justifications. Example: Maintain a registry of disabled protocols in HMIs with risk assessment data. Link: ISA technical report on ICS documentation.","url":"https://www.isa.org/standards-and-publications/isa-standards","url_description":"ISA's technical report on ICS documentation practices, pertinent to DM-4."}],"key_aspects":[{"id":"KA1","title":"Feature Risk Assessment","description":"Systematic evaluation of each feature's security impact and operational necessity, ensuring only essential components remain active. Critical for IEC 62443-4-1 compliance.","related_links":[{"title":"Honeywell ICS Risk Assessment Guide","url":"https://www.honeywellprocess.com/library/support/Pages/cybersecurity.aspx","description":"Honeywell's methodology for assessing ICS feature risks, aligned with DM-4."},{"title":"NIST Guide to Industrial Control System Security","url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-82/rev-2/final","description":"NIST SP 800-82 Rev.2 guidelines for ICS feature hardening."}]},{"id":"KA2","title":"Change Management Integration","description":"Formal processes to track and authorize feature modifications, ensuring accountability and compliance with security policies.","related_links":[{"title":"Mitsubishi Electric ICS Change Management","url":"https://www.mitsubishielectric.com/fa/products/cnt/plccpu/security/index.html","description":"Mitsubishi's framework for managing ICS configuration changes."},{"title":"Yokogawa Security Configuration Guide","url":"https://www.yokogawa.com/solutions/products-platforms/control-system/security/","description":"Yokogawa's approach to secure ICS feature management."}]},{"id":"KA3","title":"Legacy System Considerations","description":"Strategies for handling deprecated features in older ICS equipment where removal may not be feasible without operational disruption.","related_links":[{"title":"ABB Legacy System Security Whitepaper","url":"https://new.abb.com/control-systems/seguridad","description":"ABB's recommendations for securing legacy ICS features."},{"title":"Emerson Migration Strategies for ICS","url":"https://www.emerson.com/en-us/automation/plantweb","description":"Emerson's guide to modernizing legacy ICS architectures."}]},{"id":"KA4","title":"Residual Risk Documentation","description":"Recording accepted risks after feature modification, including justification for retained vulnerabilities per IEC 62443-4-1 requirements.","related_links":[{"title":"GE Digital Residual Risk Framework","url":"https://www.ge.com/digital/iiot-platform","description":"GE's methodology for documenting ICS risk decisions."},{"title":"Phoenix Contact Security Whitepapers","url":" https://www.phoenixcontact.com/online/portal/us?1dmy&urile=wcm%3apath%3a/usen/web/main/products/subcategory_pages/Industrial_communication_security_P-07-01-01/fa9ccb7e-0d8c-4b8f-9e0a-3b4e5a8d8e5a","description":"Phoenix Contact's security documentation practices for ICS."}]}],"name":"Addressing security-related issues","description":"A process shall be employed for addressing security-related issues and determining whether to report them based on the results of the impact assessment. The supplier shall establish an acceptable level of residual risk that shall be applied when determining appropriate way to address each issue. Options include one or more of the following: 4) disabling or removing features;","details":{"risk_assessment_and_threat_modeling":{"why":"To systematically identify and evaluate security-related issues and their potential impact on ICS.","methodologies":[{"name":"STRIDE","description":"A threat modeling methodology that categorizes threats into Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Information Disclosure, Denial of Service, and Elevation of Privilege."},{"name":"ICS-specific threat models","description":"Tailored threat models focusing on ICS environments, considering operational technology (OT) constraints and legacy systems."}],"tools":[{"name":"Microsoft Threat Modeling Tool","purpose":"Facilitates the creation of threat models using STRIDE and helps in identifying security issues."},{"name":"NIST 800-30 adapted for SCADA systems","purpose":"Provides a framework for conducting risk assessments in ICS environments, including impact assessments."}],"case_study":{"example":"A power plant conducted a risk assessment using NIST 800-30 adapted for SCADA systems, identifying critical vulnerabilities in a DCS. The assessment led to the disabling of non-essential features to mitigate risks."}},"audit_and_compliance_verification":{"why":"To ensure the process for addressing security-related issues is consistently applied and compliant with IEC 62443-4-1.","audit_checklist":["Verify the existence of a documented process for addressing security-related issues.","Check if impact assessments are conducted for identified issues.","Review records of decisions made regarding disabling or removing features."],"metrics":[{"kpi":"Percentage of security issues addressed within the defined timeframe","target":"≥95%"},{"kpi":"Percentage of residual risk levels within acceptable limits","target":"100%"}],"compliance_procedure":"Document the process for addressing security issues, including impact assessments and decision-making criteria. Maintain records of all actions taken, such as disabling or removing features, and review them periodically for compliance."},"training_and_competency_requirements":{"why":"To ensure personnel are competent in identifying, assessing, and addressing security-related issues in ICS.","training_programs":[{"name":"ISA/IEC 62443 Cybersecurity Certifications","description":"Provides training on IEC 62443 standards, including risk assessment and mitigation strategies."},{"name":"GICSP (Global Industrial Cyber Security Professional)","description":"Focuses on ICS security, including threat modeling and risk management."}],"competency_assessment":"Annual competency reviews to ensure personnel are proficient in threat modeling, risk assessment, and decision-making for security issues."},"tooling_and_automation_support":{"why":"To streamline the process of identifying and addressing security-related issues, ensuring consistency and efficiency.","tools":[{"name":"SIEM (Security Information and Event Management)","purpose":"Monitors and analyzes security events in real-time, helping to identify potential issues."},{"name":"Vulnerability Management Tools","purpose":"Automates the scanning and identification of vulnerabilities in ICS components."}],"automation_strategy":"Integrate vulnerability management tools with DevSecOps pipelines to automatically flag and prioritize security issues for remediation, including disabling or removing features when necessary."},"handling_legacy_systems_and_constraints":{"why":"Legacy ICS components may not support modern security standards, requiring alternative strategies to address security issues.","strategies":[{"approach":"Network segmentation","description":"Isolate legacy systems in segmented networks to limit exposure to potential threats."},{"approach":"Compensating controls","description":"Implement additional controls, such as intrusion detection systems, to mitigate risks when features cannot be disabled or removed."}],"example_policy":"A policy for legacy systems mandates that if a feature cannot be disabled or removed due to operational constraints, compensating controls must be implemented and documented in the 