    {"practice":"7","code":"SUM-1","subCode":"(1) security updates created by the product developer address the intended security vulnerabilities","explanation":"Security updates must be verified to ensure they effectively mitigate the vulnerabilities they are designed to address. This involves rigorous testing and validation processes.","context":"In industrial control systems (ICS), unverified updates can introduce new vulnerabilities or fail to resolve existing ones, compromising system integrity and safety.","challenges":["Ensuring compatibility with legacy ICS components, which may not support modern update mechanisms.","Example: A PLC from 2010 may not accept firmware updates designed for newer models.","Managing the testing environment to accurately replicate production systems for validation.","Example: Differences in network configurations between test and production can lead to undetected issues.","Addressing zero-day vulnerabilities that require rapid but thorough update validation.","Example: A critical vulnerability in a SCADA system requires immediate patching without disrupting operations.","Coordinating updates across multi-vendor environments where interoperability is critical.","Example: A patch for a Siemens device may affect communication with a Rockwell Automation component.","Ensuring updates do not impact system performance or real-time operation requirements.","Example: A security update that increases latency in a control loop could disrupt process stability."],"best_practices":[{"description":"Implement a staged rollout process to test updates in a controlled environment before full deployment.","url":" https://www.siemens.com/global/en/products/automation/industry-software/automation-software/tia-portal.html","url_description":"Siemens TIA Portal documentation on staged updates for ICS environments."},{"description":"Use automated testing tools to validate updates against known vulnerabilities and system configurations.","url":" https://ww