    {"practice":"7","code":"SUM-5","subCode":"c) Whether published exploits exist for the vulnerability;","explanation":"The requirement mandates a structured process to define and enforce a policy for timely delivery and qualification of security patches, prioritizing vulnerabilities with known exploits to mitigate immediate risks.","context":"In industrial control systems (ICS), delayed patch deployment can expose critical infrastructure to cyber threats, especially when exploits are publicly available, increasing the attack surface.","challenges":["Identifying vulnerabilities with published exploits in ICS components due to limited visibility into third-party software dependencies. Example: A PLC vendor's firmware may have an unpatched vulnerability with a known exploit, but the ICS operator is unaware.","Balancing patch urgency with operational continuity in high-availability environments. Example: A power plant may delay patching a SCADA system to avoid unplanned downtime, despite known exploits.","Qualifying patches for ICS-specific configurations without disrupting process control. Example: A patch for an RTU may require regression testing to ensure compatibility with legacy protocols.","Coordinating patch delivery across multi-vendor ICS ecosystems. Example: A DCS may integrate components from Siemens, Rockwell, and Honeywell, each with different patch cycles.","Managing legacy systems that no longer receive vendor support. Example: A gas pipeline using Windows XP-based HMIs may lack patches for exploits like WannaCry."],"best_practices":[{"description":"Maintain an updated inventory of ICS assets and their software versions to track vulnerabilities with published exploits. Example: Use tools like Tenable.ot to map vulnerabilities to ICS devices.","url":"https://www.tenable.com/solutions/operational-technology","url_description":"Tenable's OT security solution for asset discovery and vulnerability management."},{"description":"Establish a risk-based patching priority matrix that weighs exploit availability, CVSS scores, and system criticality. Example: Prioritize patching HMIs with public RCE exploits over non-exploitable vulnerabilities.","url":" https://www.cisa.gov/resources-tools/services/shieldsvulnerability-validation-system","url_description":"CISA's SHIELDS program for ICS vulnerability prioritization."},{"description":"Implement a staged patch rollout with testing in a mirrored ICS environment. Example: Test patches for a water treatment plant's PLCs in a sandbox before production deployment.","url":" https://www.siemens.com/global/en/products/automation/industry-software/automation-software/pcs-7.html","url_description":"Siemens PCS 7 documentation on patch testing methodologies."},{"description":"Leverage vendor-specific security bulletins and exploit databases like ICS-CERT. Example: Subscribe to Siemens ProductCERT for exploit notifications.","url":"https://cert-portal.siemens.com/productcert/html/security-advisories.html","url_description":"Siemens ProductCERT portal for ICS vulnerability alerts."}],"key_aspects":[{"id":"KA1","title":"Exploit Availability Assessment","description":"Systematic evaluation of vulnerability databases (e.g., CVE, ExploitDB) to identify ICS components with published exploits, enabling targeted patch prioritization. Aligns with SUM-5(c) by focusing on active threats.","related_links":[{"title":"ICS-CERT Advisories","url":"https://www.cisa.gov/ics-cert-advisories","description":"CISA's repository of ICS vulnerabilities with exploit status."},{"title":"MITRE ATT&CK for ICS","url":"https://attack.mitre.org/matrices/ics/","description":"Tactics for exploit-based attacks on industrial systems."}]},{"id":"KA2","title":"Patch Qualification Framework","description":"Structured process to validate patches in ICS environments without disrupting control logic. Includes regression testing for protocol compatibility (e.g., Modbus, DNP3). Critical for SUM-5(c) compliance.","related_links":[{"